AN ACT relating to civil liability; providing immunity from civil liability to the
State of Nevada, certain institutions of higher education and certain
officers or employees thereof under certain circumstances; and
providing other matters properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Under existing law, the State of Nevada: (1) waives its immunity from liability in civil
2 actions; and (2) consents to have its liability determined in accordance with the same rules of
3 law governing civil actions against natural persons and corporations. (NRS 41.031) Existing
4 law creates certain exceptions to this waiver of immunity from liability, thereby providing
5 immunity from liability to certain state actors under certain circumstances. (NRS 41.032-
6 41.036) Section 1 of this bill provides that the State, any university, state college or
7 community college which is part of the Nevada System of Higher Education and any officer
8 or employee thereof are immune from civil liability for any damages sustained as a result of
9 certain acts or omissions of the State, institution of higher education, officer or employee in
10 response to or on the basis of the public-health crisis caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
11 Section 2 of this bill provides that the State retains its immunity from liability in cases where
12 immunity is granted under section 1. Section 3 of this bill provides that the immunity from
13 liability granted by section 1 applies retroactively to any action commenced on or after March
14 12, 2020, for which a final judgment has not been rendered. Section 4 of this bill provides that
15 the immunity from liability granted by section 1 expires by limitation on June 30, 2030.
THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, REPRESENTED IN
SENATE AND ASSEMBLY, DO ENACT AS FOLLOWS:
1 Section 1. Chapter 41 of NRS is hereby amended by adding thereto a new
2 section to read as follows:
3 1. The State of Nevada, any institution of higher education and any officer
4 or employee thereof are immune from civil liability for damages sustained as a
5 result of an act or omission of the State, institution, officer or employee in
6 response to or on the basis of the public-health crisis caused by the COVID-19
7 pandemic which impacted the provision of educational services by an institution
8 of higher education during the spring semester of 2020 if:

Senate Amendment No. 143 to Senate Bill No. 406 Page 4
1 (a) The act or omission was reasonably related to public health and safety
2 and was performed in good faith; and
3 (b) The claim arises out of or in connection with tuition or fees paid to an
4 institution of higher education for the spring semester of 2020.
5  The Legislature declares that the purpose of this subsection is to advance the
6 compelling state interest in safeguarding the State Treasury, ensuring the
7 stability and long-term sustainability of institutions of higher education and
8 encouraging the State and its institutions of higher education to respond
9 effectively to future health crises in alignment with federal, state and local
10 guidance.
11 2. For the purposes of subsection 1, an act or omission of the State, any
12 institution of higher education or any officer or employee thereof shall be deemed
13 to have:
14 (a) Impacted the provision of educational services by an institution of higher
15 education during the spring semester of 2020 if the act or omission:
16 (1) Caused the cessation of educational services for any period;
17 (2) Caused the closure of a campus or facility operated by or under the
18 control of an institution of higher education in whole or in part or otherwise
19 limited access to any such campus or facility in whole or in part;
20 (3) Modified the manner in which educational services were provided,
21 including, without limitation, by authorizing or requiring a transition to online or
22 otherwise remote instruction; or
23 (4) Otherwise interfered with the provision of educational services.
24 (b) Been performed in good faith if the act or omission was a good faith
25 effort to comply with any applicable:
26 (1) Federal, state or local law, regulation or ordinance; or
27 (2) Written order , directive or other document published by a federal,
28 state or local government or regulatory body.
29 3. The immunity granted by this section is in addition to any other
30 immunity recognized by law, and all such immunities are cumulative, so that the
31 application or attempted application of any one does not bar the application or
32 attempted application of any other.
33 4. As used in this section:
34 (a) “Educational services” means any offering, program or benefit provided
35 by or in connection with an institution of higher education. The term includes,
36 without limitation, educational instruction, academic support services and
37 student services, regardless of whether such services are provided directly by the
38 institution of higher education or by external entities as ancillary to student
39 engagement or development.
40 (b) “Institution of higher education” means a university, state college or
41 community college which is part of the Nevada System of Higher Education.
42 (c) “Student services” means any program, resource or support activity
43 provided by or in connection with an institution of higher education for the
44 purpose of enhancing the academic, personal or professional development of
45 students. The term includes, without limitation, career services, health services
46 and ancillary student activities or extracurricular programs.
47 Sec. 2. NRS 41.031 is hereby amended to read as follows:
48 41.031 1. The State of Nevada hereby waives its immunity from liability
49 and action and hereby consents to have its liability determined in accordance with
50 the same rules of law as are applied to civil actions against natural persons and
51 corporations, except as otherwise provided in NRS 41.032 to 41.038, inclusive, and
52 section 1 of this act, 485.318, subsection 3 and any statute which expressly
53 provides for governmental immunity, if the claimant complies with the limitations

